article.headline: Stojakovic fills it up for 26
article.linkText: Kings ride Webber's big third period past Utah
article.story: SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Sacramento Kings were more than 500 miles away from home Friday -- but they never felt more at home. The Kings stretched their winning streak at the Delta Center to nine games with a 109-102 win over the Utah Jazz. Chris Webber and Paja Stojakovic are two of the biggest reasons the Kings have found a home away from home. Webber scored 14 of his 25 points in the third quarter to help the Kings take the lead. Stojakovic finished it by scoring 13 of his 26 points in the final six minutes of the game. Mike Bibby and Brad Miller both finished with 17 points for the Kings, who shot 52 percent from the field. Carlos Boozer led the Jazz with 25 points and 10 rebounds and Mehmet Okur added 15 points and nine rebounds. "I think our style is just beating their style for whatever reason," Webber said. "Maybe because the first taste of the playoffs we had was here and they sent us away. We'll always remember that." Webber keyed a 9-0 run early in the third quarter that gave Sacramento a 66-58 lead. After going 2-of-9 from the field the first half, Webber was 7-of-8 in the third quarter, including three dunks. Webber's jumper gave Sacramento a 76-68 lead with 2:05 left in the quarter, and Mike Bibby closed out the scoring in the period by converting a three-point play with 47 seconds left to make it 81-70. The Kings continued to stretch their lead in the fourth quarter. Mike Evans opened the quarter with a rebound dunk off a missed shot from Darius Songaila. After Boozer answered for the Jazz by sinking a 20-foot jumper, Evans took a feed from Bibby and slammed home another dunk that gave the Kings an 85-72 lead with 11:20 left. Webber gave the Kings their biggest lead when he banked in a 12-foot jumper off the glass to put Sacramento up 87-72. Utah cut the Kings lead to 89-81 at the 8:54 mark thanks to a 3-pointer from Raul Lopez. He was followed by a Curtis Borchardt layup and a Kirk Snyder steal and layup. Then Stojakovic heated up. The biggest of his clutch shots in the fourth quarter was a 3-pointer that banked in with 2:46 left that gave the Kings a 106-94 lead. Boozer and Keith McLeod kept the Jazz close. They each scored eight points in the quarter, but after a Boozer jumper cut the lead to 107-99 with 42 seconds remaining, Webber finished off the Jazz with another dunk. "Sometimes things happen where for whatever reason you have an ability to beat the other team," said Sacramento coach Rick Adelman. "We know when we come here they'll play hard and they'll come at us and were usually ready to play." In addition to nine straight wins in Utah, Sacramento has now won 14 of the last 17 games with the Jazz. "I thought we had a wonderful chance to win the game," Boozer said. "But Chris Webber got hot in the third quarter and we dug ourselves a hole and we couldn't get over the hump." Utah led by as many as nine points in the first half. Boozer scored nine points in the second quarter to help the Jazz to a 36-27 lead with 8:37 left in the half, but Miller scored nine points in the quarter to help the Kings go into the locker room tied at 53. ^ODDS AND ENDS:@ Sacramento center Greg Ostertag made his first appearance at the Delta Center after signing with the Kings as a free agent. Ostertag played nine seasons in Utah. He went scoreless in just four minutes of playing time... Jazz guard Raja Bell returned to the lineup Friday night after missing one game with an inflamed right knee. Friday night's game marked the first time in franchise history that the Jazz played on New Year's Eve.
